methods.name: getDate
methods.description: Get the day of the month. It is returned as a value between 1 and 31.

methods.name: setDate
methods.description: Set the day of the month in the date object as a value from 1 to 31.

methods.name: getDay
methods.description: Get the day of the week as a value from 0 to 6

methods.name: getHours
methods.description: The value returned is 0 through 23.

methods.name: setHours
methods.description: Set the hours in the date object with a value of 0 through 23.

methods.name: getMinutes
methods.description: The value returned is 0 through 59.

methods.name: setMinutes
methods.description: Set the minutes in the date object with a value of 0 through 59.

methods.name: getMonth
methods.description: Returns the month from the date object as a value from 0 through 11.

methods.name: setMonth
methods.description: Set the month in the date object as a value of 0 through 11.

methods.name: getSeconds
methods.description: The value returned is 0 through 59.

methods.name: setSeconds
methods.description: Set the seconds in the date object with a value of 0 through 59.

methods.name: getYear
methods.description: Returns the numeric digit value of the year (fullYear-1900).

methods.name: getFullYear
methods.description: Returns the numeric four digit value of the year.

methods.name: setYear
methods.description: Set the year in the date instance as a 4 digit numeric value.

methods.name: getTime
methods.description: The number of milliseconds since January 1, 1970. this function allows you to manipulate the date object based on a millisecond value then convert it back to the form you want.

methods.name: setTime
methods.description: Sets time on the basis of number of milliseconds since January 1, 1970. The below example sets the date object to one hour in the future.

methods.name: getTimezoneOffset
methods.description: Time zone offset in minutes which is the difference between GMT and local time.

methods.name: parse
methods.description: The number of milliseconds after midnight January 1, 1970 till the given date espressed as a string in the example which is IETF format.

methods.name: toGMTString
methods.description: Convert date to GMT format in a form similar to "Fri, 29 Sep 2000 06:23:54 GMT".

methods.name: UTC
methods.description:
Based on a comma delimited string, the number of milliseconds after midnight January 1, 1970 GMT is returned. The syntax of the string is "year, month, day [, hrs]
[, min] [, sec]
". An example is "2000, 9, 29, 5, 43, 0" for Sept 29, 2000 at 5:43:0. The string is considered to be GMT. The hours, minutes, and seconds are optional.

classes.name: Command
classes.description:
Executes a command in the host operating system.

Commands are dependent on the host operating system default shell.

Example: com = new Command("ls"); com.execute(true); // makes the call blocking output = com.getOutput();

methods.name: execute
methods.description:
Executes the command.

Standard output is redirected to the output attribute.

methods.name: executeAndLog
methods.description: Executes the command and logs the standard output to a file.

classes.description: Representation of a file on a managed computer.

methods.name: write
methods.description: Writes the content to the file. If the file does not exist, it is created.

methods.name: renameTo
methods.description: Renames the file denoted by this abstract pathname. Many aspects of the behavior of this method are inherently platform-dependent: The rename operation might not be able to move a file from one filesystem to another, it might not be atomic, and it might not succeed if a file with the destination abstract pathname already exists. The return value should always be checked to make sure that the rename operation was successful.

methods.name: createFile
methods.description: Creates the file if it does not exist. Also creates its directory if needed.

methods.name: createDirectory
methods.description: Creates the directory structure if it does not exist.

methods.name: deleteFile
methods.description: Deletes the file from the file system.

methods.name: canWrite

methods.name: open
methods.description:
Opens the file for reading.

Once open an index in the file is maintained. This means you can do succesive readLine.

methods.name: readLine
methods.description:
Reads one line from the opened file.

To go back to the start of the file, close it and re-open it.

methods.name: readAll
methods.description: Reads all lines from the opened file.

methods.name: open
methods.description: Opens the file for writing. From this point on the file is locked. Use close to release it.

methods.name: clean
methods.description: Reinitializes the length to 0 and sets the file-pointer in the very begining of the file.

methods.name: writeLine
methods.description: Writes a line to the file. The file must be opened first using open.

methods.name: write

methods.name: close
methods.description: Closes a previously opened file.

methods.description:
Checks if the parameter is valid host name. Example use: 
 new URL().isValidHostname(hostname)

methods.name: isValidHostnameOrIPAddress
methods.description:
Checks if the parameter is valid host name or IP address (both IPv4 and IPv6). Example use: 
 new URL().isHostnameOrIPAddress(hostOrIP)

methods.name: isValidIPAddress

Checks if the parameter is valid IP address (both IPv4 and IPv6). Example use:

methods.name: isValidIPv6Address

methods.name: escapeHost
methods.description: Escapes the host if this is needed. Usually you need to escape IPv6 numeric addresses using brackets. If this host does not need to be escaped then the original is returned.

methods.name: unescapeHost
methods.description: Un-escapes the host if this is IPv6 address in brackets. Usually you need to escape IPv6 numeric addresses using brackets but some times you need the plain IPv6 address. If this is not escaped IPv6 address the original is returned.
